What You Check in Visitor 1

You should detect declaration-related errors early:

Class Errors
Duplicate class names
Parent class does not exist
Inheritance cycles
Field Errors
Duplicate fields in same class

(Field shadowing across inheritance is allowed.)

Method Errors
Illegal overloads
Invalid overrides
Duplicate methods in same class

This is the hardest part.

You’ll need to implement the MiniJava overloading rule carefully.

Variable Errors
Duplicate parameters
Duplicate local variables
Local variable conflicts with parameter

(Remember: locals shadow fields, but locals cannot duplicate locals/params.)

Offset Calculation

This phase is ideal for offsets because now all declarations are known.

You compute:

Field offsets




Phase 2 — Semantic / Type Checking Visitor

This visitor uses the symbol tables from phase 1.

Its job is:

“Is everything used correctly?”

What Visitor 2 Checks
Expressions
1 + true → error
a && 5 → error
arr[true] → error
Assignments
A a;
B b;

a = b; // OK if B extends A

Need subtype checking.

Method Calls

You must:

Find candidate methods
Resolve overloads
Check argument compatibility
Detect ambiguity

This is the trickiest semantic part.

Return Statements

Returned expression type must match method return type.

Conditions
if (x)
while (x)

x must be boolean.

Array Operations
Index must be int
Assigned values must be int
.length only on arrays